records.addlTxt:
Defendant Nyteria Renee Banks in court.  Attorney Joseph Thomas Domask in court for Nyteria Renee Banks.  Prosecuting attorney Tyler James Rubenzer in court for the State of Wisconsin. 
Case in court for Plea and Sentencing Hearing. Parties have reached a resolution. State placed negotiations on the record. Defense counsel and defendant confirms. 

AS TO COUNT 1: 
Defendant was advised of constitution rights and maximum penalties, waived all rights and entered a plea of GUILTY.  Defendant examined as to the plea.  Stipulation by parties to complaint as a factual basis to sustain the guilty plea. Defendant advised that if not a United States Citizen, deportation is possible.  Court found that defendant knowingly, voluntarily and intelligently waived her rights.  Court found defendant guilty and ordered a Judgment of Conviction be entered on the record. 
 
Sentencing proceeded.  Statements by the State, defense and defendant.    
AS TO COUNT 1:
Defendant ordered to serve 60 DAYS in the House of Correction, credit of 6 days time served, Huber Privileges for work. Court STAYED the sentence and placed the defendant on probation for 12 months with the following conditions:

- Sign up for probation no later than 5pm on 11/4/2022.
- No possession of firearms unless for firearms safety course
- Complete a Firearms Safety Course
- Submit a DNA sample by 5pm on 11/4/2022 and pay the surcharge during probation.  Failure to pay will result in a civil judgment.
- Pay all MANDATORY costs, fees and surcharges during probation. Failure to pay will result in a civil judgment.
- Defendant advised of her right to appeal.
- Court finds the defendant was under the age of 25 at the time of the offense, the charge is a Misdemeanor, society would not be harmed and the defendant would benefit by expungement. Court grants expungement upon successful completion of the sentence.
